"Quick" in this case refers to the fact that you don't have to go 
through a lot of menus to reach the save function. It basically does 
the same thing as saving "for real".

The loading also takes a lot of time because it has to load quite a lot 
of stuff, and the context switching kicks in. The engine loads stuff on 
demand basis, meaning there might be a lot of them. IDE disks don't do 
any good either I'm afraid.

> I upgraded to 32X CDRom. Intro video still plays 'jerky' on my 060
> ppc 160mhz. Do I need faster PPC just to play normally intro video? I
> tried this video on my friend's PPC but on 240mhz, it plays very
> smoothly, without gfx 'rubbish' appearing over the screen.

IDE I presume? The problem is the IDE bus' hunger for CPU-Time. Unless 
you have a DMA controller, or SCSI, then the IDE will eat away approx. 
70% of the 68k CPU, which will have problems mixing the sound.

> When I switch screen with Amiga + M from Heretic2 to Workbench
> [Magellan, where now I'm typing this email], and then switch back to
> game screen, only letters ['loading game' etc etc] appears corrupted.
> I snapshotted this screen, so you can see it if you want].

Are these letter pixel-swapped, i.e. two adjacent pixels are swapped? 
This might happen some times and is due to some internal workings of 
the graphics chip resp. CyberGraphX. I've noticed this from time to 
time in Decent... 

Does this go away at the next screen update?

