Hi Oliver.

> I hate that motherf***ing BVision card and the whole AmigaPPC
> solution. When I play Quake (Software Renderer) on a PC with P2/160MHz
> and a 2MB SVGA card, it runs A LOT faster than ANY version on my
> PPC/175MHz and 8MB 3D card. I don't know what those people at Phase5
> smoked when they designed those 68k/PPC dual boards. No wonder they
> went down...

I agree that it is a less than optimal solution. With the software
renderer the biggest problem (I should think) is the slow bus speed
between the PPC and the BVision. IIRC it's only 20mb/sec, and even a
cheap PCI 2mb video card should get several times that amount available.
I'm not sure about RAM performance either, but that might not be as good
as the PC either.

With the Permidia2 drawing the screen, overdraw can slow it down a fair
bit too. Quake is well known for it's massive overdraw (rendering a
polygon and then drawing over all or part of it with another one,
wasting the effort of drawing it in the first place). The slow bus again
slows things down. On my brothers Cyrix 333 (note that these CPUs are
shite, FPU performance is about the same as a P166 apparently) with a
PCI 32mb RivaTNT 2 GL Quake runs very nicely in 800x600 at around 25-30
fps. Here the limit is obviously the Cyrix and perhaps to some extent
the PCI bus, my friend with the same card but using AGPx4 on a PIII
800mhz gets over 100fps easily on many games. He even gets more out of
Quake III than I do from Quake I!

Perhaps the Mediator will allow greater bus speeds. Personally I'd like
to see PCI/AGP on a PPC only card, or Amiga OS running nativly (even
under 68k emulation) on an IMac which of cource has PCI/AGP available.
MorphOS may provide this but of cource, as it stupidly uses PowerUP, it
won't run Warp3D.

